# Test Structure

## Naming
- Test files mirror source files: `auth.py` -> `test_auth.py`, `Auth.tsx` -> `Auth.test.tsx`
- Test names describe the scenario, not the method: `test_expired_token_returns_401`
- Group related tests in classes or describe blocks

## Organization
- Follow Arrange-Act-Assert (Given-When-Then) pattern
- One logical assertion per test (multiple asserts on one result is fine)
- Keep tests independent — no ordering dependencies or shared mutable state
- Use factories/fixtures for test data, not copy-pasted literals

## What to Test
- Test behavior, not implementation details
- Cover: happy path, edge cases, error cases, boundary values
- Test the public API, not private internals
- Integration tests for critical flows (auth, payments, data pipelines)

## What NOT to Test
- Framework internals (don't test that React renders a div)
- Simple getters/setters with no logic
- Third-party library behavior
- Generated code

## Test Speed
- Unit tests should run in <100ms each
- Mock external dependencies (APIs, databases, filesystems)
- Use in-memory databases for integration tests when possible
- Run slow tests in a separate suite (mark with `@pytest.mark.slow` or `.skip`)
